kha brgya pa|The sūtra contains the only known reference to a nāga king and kiṃnara king who both have this name in Sanskrit. The nāga’s name was translated into Tibetan as “hundred mouths” ({kha brgya pa}), and the kiṃnara as “hundred faces” ({bzhin brgya pa}). Other deities with the name Śatamukha appear in Indian literature.
